\begin_layout Subsection*
c.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dynamical system is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t+1}=\phi(k_{t})=\frac{sf(k_{t})+(1-\delta)k_{t}}{1+n}=\frac{f(k_{t})}{3}=\begin{cases}
\frac{6k_{t}-k_{t}^{2}}{3} & k_{t}\leq2\\
\frac{2k_{t}+4}{3} & k_{t}>2
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The steady state 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{k}$
\end_inset

 is defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t+1}=k_{t}\Rightarrow\begin{cases}
\frac{6\bar{k}-\bar{k}^{2}}{3}=\bar{k} & \bar{k}\leq2\\
\frac{2\bar{k}+4}{3}=\bar{k} & \bar{k}>2
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first case there is no solution, as it implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{k}\in\{0,3\}$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{k}\leq2$
\end_inset

.
 The second case leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{k}=4$
\end_inset

 which is consistent with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{k}>2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The output in this state is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=2K_{t}+4L_{t}=2\cdot\bar{k}\cdot L+4\cdot L=12L
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to this dynamical system, starting with a small capital value
 (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{0}\approx0$
\end_inset

), the capital will grow over time and eventually converge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
d.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that individuals save their entire first period income, the saving
 equals the total wages income:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t+1}=\phi(k_{t})=s_{t}=w_{t}=\begin{cases}
k_{t}^{2} & k_{t}\leq2\\
4 & k_{t}>2
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to this dynamical system, starting with a small capital value
 (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{0}\approx0$
\end_inset

), the capital will converge to 0 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}<1\Rightarrow k_{t+1}=k_{t}^{2}<k_{t}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the non-trivial steady state is only reachable if starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}>1$
\end_inset

 - in such case it would indeed converge.
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{k}=4$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The models yield different results, as the Solow model does not account
 for the presence of an older generation at any moment of time, which only
 consumes and does not produce.
 In the overlapping generations model the saving rate of the economy is
 in fact lower than in the Solow model (with the particular given numbers)
 - therefore, starting from low capital, the economy is unable to sustain
 growth, but only consumes everything.
\end_layout

